{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_014RGop6yyPCSfQhaeYpDM6X","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_019sE1Co4dzGBS7gBKu9MGC8","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The cron parser rejects invalid expressions (month 13, day 32, malformed syntax) with a descriptive error message","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure syntactic/semantic validation of a cron string. No I/O, no timezone complexity, no system dependencies. A mock-miss question: could a unit test catch this? Yes—pass invalid input directly to the parser, verify the error. The failure is in the parsing logic itself, not in downstream effects. A real failure would occur when you call the parser with invalid input; a unit test calling the parser directly catches this.","test_description":"Create unit tests that pass invalid cron expressions (month=13, day=32, invalid characters, missing fields) directly to the parser function and verify it rejects each with a descriptive error message (not a generic exception). Use a parametrized test to cover the full range of invalid cases.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.95,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The next-run-time calculator returns correct timestamps for standard cron expressions, including edge cases like 'last day of month' and 'nearest weekday'","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic calendar math: given a cron expression and a start time, compute the next N run times. No I/O, no system calls, no randomness. A unit test can inject a known start time (e.g., January 30, 2026) and verify the computed next run time (e.g., Feb 28 for month-end, or the nearest weekday). Mock-miss question: could mocking the input time and verifying the output miss this failure? No—if the algorithm is wrong, wrong output is detected immediately.","test_description":"Create unit tests with parameterized cron expressions and start times: (1) '0 12 L * *' (last day of month) starting Jan 15 → verify next run is Feb 28; (2) '0 9 15W * *' (nearest weekday to 15th) with dates spanning weekends → verify it selects the correct weekday. Mock the current time as input; verify output timestamps without touching system time.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The overlap detector identifies when two schedules would fire within a configured minimum gap and reports the conflicting time windows","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is pure logic: given two schedule objects and a gap duration, determine if their firing times are within the gap. The schedules are data objects; the detector is a function. No I/O, no external calls. A unit test creates or mocks two schedule objects, calls the detector, and verifies the result. Mock-miss question: could a mock schedule miss this? Only if the mock's fire-time method is broken, but the detector algorithm itself is testable in isolation.","test_description":"Create unit tests with two schedule objects whose next run times are (1) exactly within the gap (gap=300s, fires at t=0 and t=250s) → expect overlap detected, (2) exactly at the gap boundary (fires at t=0 and t=300s) → expect no overlap, (3) far apart → expect no overlap. Verify the returned conflict report includes both firing times.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Timezone-aware scheduling produces correct run times across a DST transition — a job scheduled for 2:30 AM handles the spring-forward gap and fall-back ambiguity correctly","minimum_level":"System","justification":"DST handling is system and timezone-database dependent. A unit test using a timezone library (pytz, zoneinfo) can cover the algorithm, but real failures hide in subtle interactions: code that calls datetime.now() internally, implicit system timezone reads, or timezone database differences across systems. The real failure mode is: 'the job fires at the wrong time on March 8, 2026 in America/New_York.' Only running near the actual DST boundary with the actual system timezone can reliably catch this. A unit test with mocked time may pass but fail in production on the transition date.","test_description":"Create a system test that (1) sets the system timezone to a DST-observing zone (America/New_York), (2) sets system time to March 7, 2026, 11:00 PM (before spring-forward), (3) schedules a job for 2:30 AM daily, (4) advances system time to March 8, 2026, 2:15 AM (within the gap where 2:30 AM does not exist), (5) verifies the job either fires at 3:30 AM EDT or raises a clear DST ambiguity error, not a silent skip or double-fire. Repeat for fall-back (November ambiguity).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a scheduled job's computed next run time has already passed, the engine determines whether to skip or backfill based on the job's configured missed-run policy","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is policy logic: check if next_run < now, apply the policy (skip vs. backfill). No external dependencies, no job execution, no database. A unit test creates a job object with a next_run time in the past, calls the policy handler, and verifies the returned action. The failure is in the logic; a unit test catches it directly. Real bugs (e.g., off-by-one in timestamp comparison) are caught by verifying the policy decision against the missed-run config.","test_description":"Create unit tests: (1) Job with next_run=2026-03-01 12:00, now=2026-03-01 14:00, policy='skip' → verify handler returns 'skip' action; (2) same times, policy='backfill' → verify it returns 'backfill' and computes how many runs were missed (2 if interval was 1 hour); (3) next_run exactly equals now → verify behavior is well-defined (usually 'execute now'). Test both with and without a maximum backfill limit.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13718,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13718},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"21c38973-c3a3-4b38-9515-1f5d952280bd","uuid":"6fafdd50-9ee9-410f-94fb-6ddcdeffedc6"}
